: author (L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ead </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) of the 3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">rd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, 4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and 5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Assessment reports, including the Summary for Policy Makers of the 3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">rd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> report (as Draft Author) and of the 5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> report (as Contributing Author). </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Key points:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The conclusions of the IPCC AR5 are robust. They represent the overall views of the overwhelming</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> majority of experts working on climate change</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The review by the governments and the approval process of the Summary for Policymakers clarifies the statements but do not alter them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. In no other areas of science is there such an organised and thorough asse</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ssment of the available evidence. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The details of the main report remain open to criticisms, as the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">body of evidence to review is large and exceeds in cases the capacity of the experts in charge, whose contribution to the IPCC is done in addition to their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">normal workload.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The key conclusion that the emission of anthropogenic greenhouse gases is resulting in climate warming can be considered as settled. The greatest area</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of uncertainty lie in the projection of regional climate change</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, the contribution of cl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">imate change to hurricane intensity and tropical storms,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and the response of the climate system at very high global warming levels (four degrees and above). </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The evidence presented in AR5 strengthens the case for large and rapid actions on climate change a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t both the national and international level. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.37pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The IPCC Assessments play a key role to coordinate the model experiments necessary to refine the evidence on climate change</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and should remain in some form in the future</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The process needs to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">include new ways t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o support the reviewing of the literature and to assist the researchers while solidifying the assessment at all levels. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Questions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">How robust are the conclusions in the AR5 Physical Science Basis report? Have the IPCC adequately addressed criticisms of </span><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">previous reports? How much scope is there to question of the report’s conclusions?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 31.96pt; padding-left:3.74pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The overall conclusions of the report </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">robust and little changed from previous reports. Each IPCC assessment has strengthened the results of the previous report</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, in line </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with the increasing evidence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The general conclusions that the Earth is warming, and that the emissions of greenhouse gases are causing the observed warming are stated clearly with a level of uncertainty that represents the overall </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">body of evidence. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The cl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">imate projections </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and associated compatible emissions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are based on fundamental and reliable knowledge of the physical processes that control the dynamics of the climate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and the uncertainty provided reflects the available knowledge, including from observat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The coordination of the model experiments by the World Climate Research Programme </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(the Coupled Model Intercomparison Project – CMIP5) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">means that the results are comparable and thorough, and provide a large number of results from many groups around th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e world.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Results from 47 models developed by 21 research groups were used in the report, representing all the main climate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> research</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> groups across the world. The design of these experiments is very th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rough, from all aspects of the forcing and analysis.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> report</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> itself</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is prepared by a large number of authors (259) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">covering </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">all components of the physical climate research. In no other areas of science is there such an organised and thorough assessment of the available evidence. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 31.96pt; padding-left:3.74pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">details of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">report ho</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wever </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">remain </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">open to criticism as a result of its reliance on review by a small group of experts who do not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">necessarily </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">carry out formal systematic reviews of the literature</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and because of the difficulty to keep up to date with a rapidly evolving research</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> field as the report gets written</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Although the report gets reviewed twice by experts and governments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, the body of evidence to review is large and exceeds in cases the capacity of the experts in charge, whose contribution to the IPCC is done in addition to their normal workload. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This is exemplified by the case of glacial melt in the Himalayas, statements </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">about which, were strongly criticised in the AR4 report. You might, therefore, have expected this issue to have been dealt with thoroughly in the latest report but a number of key references were missed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that have been identified in a parallel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">systematic re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">view</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (Miller, J., Rees, G., Warnaars, T., Young, G., Collins D. &amp; Shrestha, A. 2013. What is the evidence for glacial shrinkage across the Himalayas? CEE review10-008. Collaboration for Environmental Evidence: www.environmentalevidence.org/ SR10008.html)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">To what extent does AR5 reflect the range of views among climate scientists?</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This question is difficult to answer without a formal assessment, which has not been done. However, our contacts with a wide range of climate scientists indicate that AR5 does l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">argely reflect their views. This was certainly not the case in AR4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for the issue of sea level rise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> where there was considerable unease over the way in which the future projections of sea level rise were handled. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Can any of the areas of the science now be </span><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">considered settled as a result of AR5’s publication, if so which?  What areas need further effort to reduce the levels of uncertainty?</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The key conclusion that the emission of anthropogenic greenhouse gases is resulting in climate warming and ocean acidific</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ation remains robust and can be considered as settled, unless new evidence to the contrary is forthcoming. The greatest area</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of uncertainty lie in the projection of regional climate change</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, the contribution of climate change to </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hurricane intensity</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and tro</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pical storms,</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> whether or not we approaching any significant climate tipping points</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for glaciers melting and ocean circulation, and </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the size of the carbon cycle feedbacks particularly with respect to permafrost melting</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in the high warming scenarios</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">How ef</span><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">fective is AR5 and the summary for policymakers in conveying what is meant by uncertainty in scientific terms? Would a focus on risk rather than uncertainty be useful?</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">No, a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">focus on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> risk would not be useful. IPCC has a well documented and appraised approa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ch to conveying uncertainty in our knowledge, whether that relates to past historical climates or future climate projections. It would not make sense to talk about the risk associated with past historical climates; it is rather our knowledge that is uncert</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ain. Moreover risk is generally interpreted in terms of the likelihood of an event occurring and its consequences. This only relates to a subset of the findings in AR5.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> For these elements (e.g. the risk of exceeding global warming of 4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> degrees</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">), an analysis of risks would be appropriate, but this should come in addition to the current assessment of uncertainty. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Does the AR5 address the reliability of climate models?</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 31.96pt; padding-left:3.74pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Yes. The AR5 includes a full chapter on the evaluation of climate models. It e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">xplains how the models have evolved since the AR4 and what aspects of the climate system the models </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">can accurately reproduce. The models are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evaluated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">compared to the metrics of climate change (the climate sensitivity and transient climate response). This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">can be done because of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">coordination and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">availability of the appropriate model simulations requested by the CMIP5 experiments. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Results presented usually </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">represent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5-95% </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">model range for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">each scenario projection</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, which implicitly removes outliers f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rom the analysis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The IPCC process provides a major incentive to co-ordinate modelling activities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, without which it would be more difficult to make intermodal comparisons and assess the reliability of climate models.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Has AR5 sufficiently explained the re</span><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">asons behind the widely reported hiatus in the global surface temperature record?</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">AR5 provided a partial explanation of the hiatus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> available by March 2013 (the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cut-off</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> date for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">publications to be considered by the authors)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, but new information is emerging </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(e.g. Cowtan, K. and Way, R.G. 2013. Coverage bias in the HadCRUT4 temperature series and its impact on recent temperature trends. doi: 10.1002/qj.2297). The indications are that climate warming continues and that the hiatus in the global surface temperatu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">re record is a result of more heat than expected finding its way into the deep ocean and an under recording of surface temperature in the Arctic.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Do the AR5 Physical Science Basis report’s conclusions strengthen or weaken the economic case for action to </span><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">prevent dangerous climate change?</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The economic case for action to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">adaptation is strengthened by AR5. The evidence for the potentially destructive effects of climate change is greater</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. In particular there is better ev</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">idence of an increase frequency and/or intensity of some extreme events (heat waves, heavy precipitation events, and extreme high sea level), and of the contribution of climate change to these events. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he increase in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">emissions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of GHGs is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">higher th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">anticipated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in the previous report. There </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">consequently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">remains an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">overwhelming economic case for immediate action as originally outlined by Lord Stern in the Stern review on the economics of climate change in 2006.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What implications do the IPCC’s conclu</span><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">sions in the AR5 Physical Science Basis report have for policy making both nationally and internationally?</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The IPCC report reaffirms that anthropogenic greenhouse gas emissions are having a significant impact on the climate system and that significant acti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on is required both nationally and internationally to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The efforts required to limit global climate change to 2 degrees above pre-industrial levels are larger than at the time AR4 was published (in 2007) because the emission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s of greenhouse gas have continued to rise </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">between 2007 and 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-