ize:12pt">is to provide an assessment of our scientific knowledge on climate change and not to provide a justification for political commitment, although others undoubtedly use it for that purpose. Whether it remains the most effecti</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ve mechanism for assessing that k</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nowledge is however unclear.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">After AR4 there was debate over whether a periodic review was the appropriate mechanism, moving forward, or whether the focus should now turn to shorter reports that reviewed areas where there had been substantial progress or w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">here there was considerable uncertainty. One of the major advantages of the current system is that it provides a focus for modelling activities in WG1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, which are essential to review the projections of climate change. Furthermore, the assessment process pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">vides the only forum where all the components of the climate system can be looked at (e.g. the atmosphere, ocean, ice, land</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, biogeochemical cycles</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">), and consistency across different streams of research can be analysed. This is very powerful in terms of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">assessing the main conclusions of the report</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. It is not clear </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">however </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the current process </span><span styl