bri; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">akers and did not alter them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The guidance from the IPCC co-Chairs during Stockholm and throughout the process was very clear</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the results prese</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nted in the Summary for Policy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">akers must reflect the body of evidence presented in the main report. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The 10 figures shown in the Summary for Policymakers were selected by the authors and have all been approved</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Importantly, all of the key statements proposed by the authors have been cl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">arified and shortened, without </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a loss of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> substance. Thus the report and key results are understandable to a larger audience, while still containing the evidence put forward by the authors. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Is the rate at which the UK Government intends to cut CO2 emissio</span><span style="color:#7f7f7f; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ns appropriate in light of the findings of the IPCC AR5 Physical Science Basis report?</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-fa